---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Emergency Numbers & Help in Korea"
  description="Essential emergency contacts for travelers in Korea: police, ambulance, fire, the 1330 tourist hotline, and medical help — with multilingual support info."
>
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Essentials</p>
      <h1>Emergency & Help in Korea</h1>
      <p>Save these before you travel.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <article class="article wrap">
    <div class="fact-box">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>112</strong> — Police (crime, danger)</li>
        <li><strong>119</strong> — Fire & Ambulance (medical emergency)</li>
        <li>
          <strong>1330</strong> — Korea Travel Hotline (24/7, multilingual:
          English, Chinese, Japanese, and more). Your first call for anything
          travel-related — directions, interpretation, complaints.
        </li>
        <li><strong>120</strong> — Dasan Call Center (Seoul city info)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Good to know</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>1330 can interpret for you</strong> during a 112 or 119 call —
          they can conference in and translate in real time.
        </li>
        <li>Emergency calls are free from any phone, including without a SIM.</li>
        <li>
          Pharmacies (약국, <em>yakguk</em>) handle minor issues; look for the
          green cross sign.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p class="disclosure">
      Numbers are provided for convenience and were accurate at the time of
      writing. Always confirm current emergency procedures with official sources
      such as the Korea Tourism Organization (visitkorea.or.kr).
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
